		{
			"type": "text",
			"id": "kfWUjAQe",
			"x": 55,
			"y": 215,
			"width": 767.5553588867188,
			"height": 333.45,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#cdd6f4",
			"backgroundColor": "transparent",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 1,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 2039,
			"version": 2,
			"versionNonce": 1103128167,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1775994001790,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "🏠 Real-world analogy:  A Class is like a COOKIE CUTTER (mould).  An Object is each actual COOKIE baked from it.\n   One mould → thousands of unique cookies (different icing, size).  The mould itself is never eaten.\n\n🔷 Class  → Blueprint / Template defining attributes (data) + methods (behaviour)\n🔷 Object → Concrete instance living in memory, holding its own data\n\n   # Example: Dog class  (Python)\n   class Dog:\n       species = \"Canis lupus\"          # class variable  (shared by ALL dogs)\n       def __init__(self, name, breed):\n           self.name  = name            # instance variable (unique per object)\n           self.breed = breed\n       def bark(self):\n           print(f\"{self.name} says: Woof!\")\n\n   buddy  = Dog(\"Buddy\",  \"Labrador\")   # Object 1\n   shadow = Dog(\"Shadow\", \"Husky\")      # Object 2  — same blueprint, different data\n   buddy.bark()   # → \"Buddy says: Woof!\"\n   shadow.bark()  # → \"Shadow says: Woof!\"",
			"fontSize": 13,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "🏠 Real-world analogy:  A Class is like a COOKIE CUTTER (mould).  An Object is each actual COOKIE baked from it.\n   One mould → thousands of unique cookies (different icing, size).  The mould itself is never eaten.\n\n🔷 Class  → Blueprint / Template defining attributes (data) + methods (behaviour)\n🔷 Object → Concrete instance living in memory, holding its own data\n\n   # Example: Dog class  (Python)\n   class Dog:\n       species = \"Canis lupus\"          # class variable  (shared by ALL dogs)\n       def __init__(self, name, breed):\n           self.name  = name            # instance variable (unique per object)\n           self.breed = breed\n       def bark(self):\n           print(f\"{self.name} says: Woof!\")\n\n   buddy  = Dog(\"Buddy\",  \"Labrador\")   # Object 1\n   shadow = Dog(\"Shadow\", \"Husky\")      # Object 2  — same blueprint, different data\n   buddy.bark()   # → \"Buddy says: Woof!\"\n   shadow.bark()  # → \"Shadow says: Woof!\"",
			"lineHeight": 1.35,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "a5",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
