			"text": "🧬  II. Inheritance",
			"fontSize": 15,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "center",
			"verticalAlign": "middle",
			"containerId": "oop_02120",
			"originalText": "🧬  II. Inheritance",
			"lineHeight": 1.3,
			"fontWeight": 700,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "aI",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
		{
			"type": "text",
			"id": "0OaBvo5q",
			"x": 608,
			"y": 710,
			"width": 347.8197021484375,
			"height": 518.4000000000001,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#cdd6f4",
			"backgroundColor": "transparent",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 1,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 2137,
			"version": 2,
			"versionNonce": 1429073991,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1775994001790,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "🧬 Analogy: Biological inheritance.\n   You inherit eye colour, height from parents —\n   but you're still your own person (can override).\n\nChild class reuses parent's attributes + methods.\n\nSingle:        Dog  →  Animal\nMulti-level:   GoldenRetriever → Dog → Animal\n               (GoldenRetriever has ALL of Animal & Dog)\nHierarchical:  Cat, Dog, Horse  →  Animal\n\nPython example:\n  class Animal:\n      def __init__(self, name): self.name = name\n      def breathe(self): return \"inhale/exhale\"\n      def speak(self):   return \"...\"\n\n  class Dog(Animal):\n      def speak(self):   return \"Woof!\"   # override\n\n  class GoldenRetriever(Dog):\n      def fetch(self):   return \"fetching!\"\n\n  g = GoldenRetriever(\"Buddy\")\n  g.breathe()  # from Animal  → \"inhale/exhale\"\n  g.speak()    # from Dog     → \"Woof!\"\n  g.fetch()    # own method   → \"fetching!\"\n\n❌ Diamond Problem (Java classes):\n  class C extends A, B  ← if both A and B have fly(),\n  which fly() does C use?  Java says: ILLEGAL.\n  Fix → use Interfaces (C implements A, B)",
			"fontSize": 12,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "🧬 Analogy: Biological inheritance.\n   You inherit eye colour, height from parents —\n   but you're still your own person (can override).\n\nChild class reuses parent's attributes + methods.\n\nSingle:        Dog  →  Animal\nMulti-level:   GoldenRetriever → Dog → Animal\n               (GoldenRetriever has ALL of Animal & Dog)\nHierarchical:  Cat, Dog, Horse  →  Animal\n\nPython example:\n  class Animal:\n      def __init__(self, name): self.name = name\n      def breathe(self): return \"inhale/exhale\"\n      def speak(self):   return \"...\"\n\n  class Dog(Animal):\n      def speak(self):   return \"Woof!\"   # override\n\n  class GoldenRetriever(Dog):\n      def fetch(self):   return \"fetching!\"\n\n  g = GoldenRetriever(\"Buddy\")\n  g.breathe()  # from Animal  → \"inhale/exhale\"\n  g.speak()    # from Dog     → \"Woof!\"\n  g.fetch()    # own method   → \"fetching!\"\n\n❌ Diamond Problem (Java classes):\n  class C extends A, B  ← if both A and B have fly(),\n  which fly() does C use?  Java says: ILLEGAL.\n  Fix → use Interfaces (C implements A, B)",
			"lineHeight": 1.35,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "aJ",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
