			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "🎭  III. Polymorphism",
			"fontSize": 15,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "center",
			"verticalAlign": "middle",
			"containerId": "oop_02148",
			"originalText": "🎭  III. Polymorphism",
			"lineHeight": 1.3,
			"fontWeight": 700,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "aM",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
		{
			"type": "text",
			"id": "AzPpexFG",
			"x": 1168,
			"y": 710,
			"width": 354.80364990234375,
			"height": 631.8000000000001,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#cdd6f4",
			"backgroundColor": "transparent",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 1,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 2165,
			"version": 2,
			"versionNonce": 1378208391,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1775994001790,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "🎭 Analogy: A \"+\" operator.\n   1 + 2 = 3 (integer add)\n   \"Hi\" + \"!\" = \"Hi!\" (string concat)\n   Same symbol, different behaviour → polymorphism!\n\n\"Many Forms\" — one interface, multiple behaviours.\n\n━━ COMPILE-TIME (Overloading) — Java only ━━\nSame method name, different parameter signatures.\nDecided at compile time by the compiler.\n\n  int    add(int a, int b)    { return a+b; }\n  double add(double a, double b){ return a+b; }\n  String add(String a, String b){ return a+b; }\n  add(1, 2)        → 3\n  add(1.5, 2.5)    → 4.0\n  add(\"Hi\",\"!\")    → \"Hi!\"\n\nPython uses *args / default params instead.\n\n━━ RUNTIME (Overriding) ━━\nSubclass redefines parent method.\nResolved at runtime based on ACTUAL object type.\n\n  class Payment:\n      def process(self, amt): pass  # abstract-ish\n\n  class CreditCard(Payment):\n      def process(self, amt): print(f\"Charging card ${amt}\")\n\n  class UPI(Payment):\n      def process(self, amt): print(f\"UPI transfer ₹{amt}\")\n\n  payments = [CreditCard(), UPI(), CreditCard()]\n  for p in payments:\n      p.process(100)   # correct type resolved at runtime\n  → Charging card $100\n  → UPI transfer ₹100\n  → Charging card $100",
			"fontSize": 12,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "🎭 Analogy: A \"+\" operator.\n   1 + 2 = 3 (integer add)\n   \"Hi\" + \"!\" = \"Hi!\" (string concat)\n   Same symbol, different behaviour → polymorphism!\n\n\"Many Forms\" — one interface, multiple behaviours.\n\n━━ COMPILE-TIME (Overloading) — Java only ━━\nSame method name, different parameter signatures.\nDecided at compile time by the compiler.\n\n  int    add(int a, int b)    { return a+b; }\n  double add(double a, double b){ return a+b; }\n  String add(String a, String b){ return a+b; }\n  add(1, 2)        → 3\n  add(1.5, 2.5)    → 4.0\n  add(\"Hi\",\"!\")    → \"Hi!\"\n\nPython uses *args / default params instead.\n\n━━ RUNTIME (Overriding) ━━\nSubclass redefines parent method.\nResolved at runtime based on ACTUAL object type.\n\n  class Payment:\n      def process(self, amt): pass  # abstract-ish\n\n  class CreditCard(Payment):\n      def process(self, amt): print(f\"Charging card ${amt}\")\n\n  class UPI(Payment):\n      def process(self, amt): print(f\"UPI transfer ₹{amt}\")\n\n  payments = [CreditCard(), UPI(), CreditCard()]\n  for p in payments:\n      p.process(100)   # correct type resolved at runtime\n  → Charging card $100\n  → UPI transfer ₹100\n  → Charging card $100",
			"lineHeight": 1.35,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "aN",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
