		},
		{
			"type": "text",
			"id": "Chi2QoA4",
			"x": 1590,
			"y": 1344,
			"width": 357.9956970214844,
			"height": 631.8000000000001,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#cdd6f4",
			"backgroundColor": "transparent",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 1,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 2277,
			"version": 2,
			"versionNonce": 106795911,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1775994001790,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "📦 Analogy: A labelled box.\n   Box<Apple>  → can only hold Apples, type-safe.\n   Without generics you'd use Object — then need to\n   cast everywhere and get ClassCastException at runtime.\n\nWITHOUT generics (dangerous):\n  List list = new ArrayList();\n  list.add(\"hello\");\n  list.add(42);       // compiles!\n  String s = (String) list.get(1);  // 💥 runtime crash\n\nWITH generics (safe):\n  List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();\n  list.add(\"hello\");\n  list.add(42);   // ✗ compile error — caught early!\n\nGeneric method (Java):\n  <T> void print(T item) { System.out.println(item); }\n  print(42);  print(\"hi\");  print(3.14);  // one method!\n\nWildcards — when you don't know exact type:\n  ? extends Number  (Upper Bound — PRODUCER / read)\n    void sum(List<? extends Number> nums) {\n        for(Number n : nums) total += n.doubleValue();\n    }\n    → accepts List<Integer>, List<Double>, List<Float>\n    → you can READ, but NOT add new elements (unsafe)\n\n  ? super Integer  (Lower Bound — CONSUMER / write)\n    void fill(List<? super Integer> list) {\n        list.add(1); list.add(2);  // safe to write\n    }\n\nPECS principle:\n  Producer Extends  |  Consumer Super\n\nPython typing:\n  T = TypeVar('T')\n  def first(lst: list[T]) -> T: return lst[0]",
			"fontSize": 12,
			"fontFamily": 1,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "📦 Analogy: A labelled box.\n   Box<Apple>  → can only hold Apples, type-safe.\n   Without generics you'd use Object — then need to\n   cast everywhere and get ClassCastException at runtime.\n\nWITHOUT generics (dangerous):\n  List list = new ArrayList();\n  list.add(\"hello\");\n  list.add(42);       // compiles!\n  String s = (String) list.get(1);  // 💥 runtime crash\n\nWITH generics (safe):\n  List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();\n  list.add(\"hello\");\n  list.add(42);   // ✗ compile error — caught early!\n\nGeneric method (Java):\n  <T> void print(T item) { System.out.println(item); }\n  print(42);  print(\"hi\");  print(3.14);  // one method!\n\nWildcards — when you don't know exact type:\n  ? extends Number  (Upper Bound — PRODUCER / read)\n    void sum(List<? extends Number> nums) {\n        for(Number n : nums) total += n.doubleValue();\n    }\n    → accepts List<Integer>, List<Double>, List<Float>\n    → you can READ, but NOT add new elements (unsafe)\n\n  ? super Integer  (Lower Bound — CONSUMER / write)\n    void fill(List<? super Integer> list) {\n        list.add(1); list.add(2);  // safe to write\n    }\n\nPECS principle:\n  Producer Extends  |  Consumer Super\n\nPython typing:\n  T = TypeVar('T')\n  def first(lst: list[T]) -> T: return lst[0]",
			"lineHeight": 1.35,
			"autoResize": true,
			"index": "ad",
			"frameId": null,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"rawText": ""
		},
